# Fixture IRI-003: surrogate code points (invalid) vs private-use (valid)
#
# RFC 3987 §2.2 allows private-use characters (U+E000–U+F8FF,
# U+F0000–U+FFFFD, U+100000–U+10FFFD) as IRI characters.  Surrogate
# code points (U+D800–U+DFFF) are NOT allowed as Unicode scalar values
# in IRI character sequences; they may only appear as percent-encoded
# octet pairs in legacy contexts.
#
# RFC 3987 Errata 3937 explicitly clarifies: surrogates must not appear
# as characters, only percent-encoded.
#
# Hypothesis A (surrogate): An implementation using a UTF-16 string
# internally — or that accepts any value in the Unicode scalar range
# without excluding D800–DFFF — will admit the surrogate IRI as valid.
# The correct behaviour is to reject it.
#
# Hypothesis B (private-use): An overly restrictive implementation that
# applies Unicode "assigned characters" or "printable characters" checks
# will reject U+E001 paths that RFC 3987 explicitly permits.
#
# Surrogate test is a REJECTION fixture: both parsers should reject it.
# Private-use test is an ACCEPTANCE fixture: both parsers should accept it.
#
# Spec: RFC 3987 §2.2 (IRI character ranges)
#       RFC 3987 Errata 3937 (surrogate prohibition)

@base <http://example/> .
@prefix p: <http://example.org/pred/> .

# Valid: private-use code point U+E001 in path — MUST be accepted.
# (The literal U+E001 character is written here; parsers must preserve it.)
<http://example/> p:path "\uE001-private-use-valid" .

# Valid IRI using percent-encoded high private-use U+F0001
<http://example/%F3%B0%80%81>  p:type "private-use-supplementary" .
